The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 London, Sept. 9: Sahara has approached bankers here to raise between $5-7 billion to finance its development projects. According to a report in The Sunday Times, the fund will help pay for the groups plan to create 217 townships in India. As part of the fund raising, Sahara is planning to list a subsidiary company called Sahara City Homes on the London stock market, the report said.

 Tokyo, Sept. 9: Truckmaker Isuzu will make mid-sized buses in India later this month. The company will team up with Sumitomo Corp and Swaraj Mazda to set up an auto plant next to its factory in Delhi. The buses will be priced at around 1.5 million yen.

 New Delhi, Sept. 9: The expenditure on advertising by sectors such as realty and telecom, in proportion to their sales, has grown by 36 per cent and 21 per cent respectively, a study by Assocham Eco Pulse has said. However, marketing expenses in proportion to the sales of the two sectors have declined, the study added.

 New Delhi, Sept. 9: The CBI will seek help from the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India to find out how international calls were allegedly routed as local ones by Reliance Infocomm before its demerger. 

 New Delhi, Sept. 9: The International Hotel Licensing Company, an arm of the Marriott group, has moved the apex court against the ruling of a quasi judicial body which said that foreign firms were liable to pay tax on assignment fee charged from Indian companies for promotional activities abroad.

 Mobor, Sept. 9: Bajaj Auto has offered the workers of its Akurdi plant, which was closed recently, a six-day pay instead of the earlier five-and-a-half-day wages. The company took the decision after Union agriculture minister Sharad Pawar, who represents the Akurdi area in Lok Sabha, intervened in the matter.

 Beijing, Sept. 9: China will unveil financial policy changes to support overseas investment and acquisitions by Chinese companies, governor of the Peoples Bank of China Zhou Xiaochuan has said.




